l or May, when most of the tourist destinations are open. In order to avoid an overabundance of tourists, some travelers choose the months of June to August. Ladakh has lengthy winters because of its high elevation. So, scroll down to learn what to expect when you choose among the tourist places in Leh Ladakh. 1. Pangong Tso Lake The tranquil Pangong Lake, sometimes called Pangong Tso, is situated at an amazing height of 14,270 feet. The eye is immediately drawn to its clear blue waters and enormous expanse because it seems as though magic is taking place right before one's eyes. Aamir Khan's superhit film '3 Idiots' brought attention to this lake. Therefore, without question, this destination bears inclusion on one's list of Ladakh tourist attractions. It is worth noting that the lake, which is 12 km long, is between the borders of China and India. 60% of the area is reaching into the next country, which intrigues every traveler to be present. Since the seemingly clear blue waters of this lake are basically brackish or saline, no ocean animals can thrive there. However, inside the lake, a few species of crustaceans are prospering. Numerous thousands of exotic birds will be circling the lake, creating a magnificent sight. Several bird species, including migratory birds like Brahmini ducks, breed on the lake. Because the lake is always frozen in the winter, the best time to come is in the pleasant month of June. In addition, the saline lake freezes with huge ice caps and masses when the temperatures drop around -30 and -10 degrees, which is completely the reverse of what happens with salt-filled water bodies. April marks the start of the lake's melting process, while June marks its completion. There isn't much aquatic life in this saltwater body of water. To visit the lake, Indian citizens need to get an Inner Line Permit, and visitors from other countries need a Protected Area Permit. 2. Magnetic Hill One of the most enigmatic and fascinating tourist destinations in the nation is Magnetic Hill in Ladakh, which is situated at an elevation of 14,000 feet. It counts among the most visited tourist destinations in Ladakh. As this area is thought to have magnetic abilities, it is also known as Gravity Hill. Because of its strength, the magnetism can drag the vehicles up hills. In addition to being one of the unique spots to visit in Ladakh in the summer, people think that there have been natural and supernatural powers that produce magnetic attractions. As automobiles appear to be pushed upwards on this small cyclops hill, it is stated that this is a location where the laws of gravity are disobeyed. A number of scientific hypotheses may explain the enigma behind this unusual phenomenon, but there is also a widely held local belief that claims that the Magnetic Hill Road is a straight "stairway to heaven." The entrance to Magnetic Hill is marked with a white box where one is instructed to park their car and a signboard that reads, "Magnetic Hill - the Phenomenon that defies Gravity." They gradually start to move uphill on their own, against gravity, at a pace of about 10 to 20 km/h after one parks their car in neutral. The Optical Illusion is one of the most rational and scientific explanations for the Magnetic Hill. According to this theory, although the hill's slope is downhill, it tends to appear upright because of its distinctive topography, giving the impression that the vehicle is moving upward. An alternative explanation is the concept of the Earth's magnetic force, which postulates that the magnetic fields in the Earth's interior pull the vehicles upward. This is one such occurrence that has drawn vacationers to Magnetic Hill from all over the world. Whatever the reason is, Magnetic Hill is unquestionably a fantastic place to explore. It's a terrific rest stop on the Manali-Leh Highway, a great spot to take beautiful photos, chill, or take in nature. June is a great month to visit this intriguing location because the weather 