e weather would be the perfect combination. 4. Nubra Valley The tri-armed Nubra valley, which is located in northeastern Ladakh, is unquestionably among the finest places to visit. Nubra Valley, one of Ladakh's most stunning moonscapes, is a deep gorge formed by the combined forces of the Shyok and Nubra (Siachen) rivers. It is around 160 km from Leh, the capital of Ladakh, and is a major draw for visitors. The Nubra Valley, a frigid desert at a great altitude, is a continuation of the Tibetan Plateau (Qing-Zang Plateau), which begins in China and reaches Ladakh. The Ladakh Range and the Karakoram Range are divided by this valley in the plateau. The most picturesque area in all of Ladakh, though, is Nubra Valley. The valley's sand dunes give visitors a taste of the Arabian Nights. Due to its two-humped camels, Nubra valley serves as one of the most well-known tourist destinations in Leh Ladakh. The Nubra Valley, which is the entry point to the upper portions of the nation, particularly Siachen, has an oasis-like village called Diskit in its center that is a wonderful location to pause and take in the surrounding splendor. While one is at it, make a quick diversion to the renowned Hunder white sand dunes. Every traveler who comes here is mesmerized by the shapes and forms that these dunes adapt throughout the course of the year. The double-humped Bactrian camels, which provide rides across the dunes, add to the intrigue. And when it starts to get dark, go to the Diskit Monastery to check out the enormous Maitreya Buddha statue, which overlooks the entire valley and bestows blessings for yet another day. 5. Tso Moriri Lake Tso Moriri Lake, a lesser-known lake situated in the Changtang Wildlife Sanctuary, is a twin to the well-known Pangong Tso Lake. This lake's surroundings add to its beautiful splendor. The scene is stunning, with barren hills in the background and snow-capped mountains. The lake, which is around 4,000 meters above sea level, is about 29 kilometers l