o known as Gravity Hill. Because of its strength, the magnetism can drag the vehicles up hills. In addition to being one of the unique spots to visit in Ladakh in the summer, people think that there have been natural and supernatural powers that produce magnetic attractions. As automobiles appear to be pushed upwards on this small cyclops hill, it is stated that this is a location where the laws of gravity are disobeyed. A number of scientific hypotheses may explain the enigma behind this unusual phenomenon, but there is also a widely held local belief that claims that the Magnetic Hill Road is a straight "stairway to heaven." The entrance to Magnetic Hill is marked with a white box where one is instructed to park their car and a signboard that reads, "Magnetic Hill - the Phenomenon that defies Gravity." They gradually start to move uphill on their own, against gravity, at a pace of about 10 to 20 km/h after one parks their car in neutral. The Optical Illusion is one of the most rational and scientific explanations for the Magnetic Hill. According to this theory, although the hill's slope is downhill, it tends to appear upright because of its distinctive topography, giving the impression that the vehicle is moving upward. An alternative explanation is the concept of the Earth's magnetic force, which postulates that the magnetic fields in the Earth's interior pull the vehicles upward. This is one such occurrence that has drawn vacationers to Magnetic Hill from all over the world. Whatever the reason is, Magnetic Hill is unquestionably a fantastic place to explore. It's a terrific rest stop on the Manali-Leh Highway, a great spot to take beautiful photos, chill, or take in nature. June is a great month to visit this intriguing location because the weather is nice, one can explore the neighborhood, and one can feed their zest for adventure. 3. Royal Leh Palace The Royal Leh Palace stands out as one of the most impressive tourist attractions in Leh Ladakh and displays t