 downhill, it tends to appear upright because of its distinctive topography, giving the impression that the vehicle is moving upward. An alternative explanation is the concept of the Earth's magnetic force, which postulates that the magnetic fields in the Earth's interior pull the vehicles upward. This is one such occurrence that has drawn vacationers to Magnetic Hill from all over the world. Whatever the reason is, Magnetic Hill is unquestionably a fantastic place to explore. It's a terrific rest stop on the Manali-Leh Highway, a great spot to take beautiful photos, chill, or take in nature. June is a great month to visit this intriguing location because the weather is nice, one can explore the neighborhood, and one can feed their zest for adventure. 3. Royal Leh Palace The Royal Leh Palace stands out as one of the most impressive tourist attractions in Leh Ladakh and displays the opulence of a bygone period. It is also referred to as Lichen Palkhar and was formerly the residence of the Leh royal dynasty. The Palace's picturesque setting enhances its charm. It was constructed in the sixteenth century and is located above the Ladakhi town of Leh. The Palace is as tall as a nine-story structure, with the royal families residing on the upper floors and storerooms and animal stables on the bottom ones. The stunning scenery of the Ladakh mountain ranges and Stok Kangri from this Palace has made it a popular tourist destination today. From the top, one may take in sweeping vistas of the Zanskar Valley, which juxtapose with the bright blue skies just above it. Such sights are rejuvenating and a treat for the eyes, brain, and spirit. The Buddhist faith and culture place great importance on this Palace. The magnificent Buddha statue in the rear of this Palace only enhances its allure. A substantial collection of jewelry, crowns, ornaments and ceremonial clothing is on display at the Museum of the Palace. And if one enjoys learning about the past, then this is the ideal loca